    "analysis": "From the previous Executor summaries: global thresholds (P95/P5) were computed for the five candidate services. Metric analysis flagged ts-order-service as the strongest candidate: its 'error' KPI is anomalous across the entire incident window (25/25 points) and there are socket spikes as well. ts-auth-service shows multi-resource anomalies (cpu, diskio, mem, latency) with earliest anomalies around 15:14–15:22 UTC. ts-route-service shows several resource anomalies around 15:14–15:16 UTC. ts-travel-service shows a small error anomaly burst later (~15:34). Traces show many interactions between auth and order services. To apply the fault-identification and root-cause-localization rules we must (1) confirm faults are consecutive (not isolated spikes), (2) find the first occurrence time of each fault, and (3) use traces to determine downstream faulty service in call chains. The summary aggregates suggest ts-order-service.error is the most persistent anomaly, but it is unclear whether 'error' being 0 (P95=P5=0) represents a drop in a traffic/business KPI (which could indicate network/packet loss) or a telemetry artifact. We need the exact timestamped metric values within the incident window for top candidate KPIs to determine fault start times and whether anomalies are sustained consecutively.\n\nTherefore we should retrieve the raw timestamped metric points (within the incident window) for a small set of high-priority component-KPIs: ts-order-service:error, ts-order-service:socket, ts-auth-service:cpu, ts-auth-service:diskio, ts-auth-service:latency-90, ts-route-service:cpu, ts-travel-service:error. This will let us confirm consecutive faults, earliest breach times, and magnitudes to decide which service is the root cause. Trace and log evidence will be used next after confirming metric fault timing.",
