    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing and metric anomaly detection. Key observations from metric time series inside the incident window: (1) ts-order-service:error is flagged across the entire window (25 samples) but the metric values are all 0.0 (global P95/P5 were 0), which can be ambiguous: it may represent no errors (healthy) or a drop in a business/traffic KPI (if this metric normally has >0 values). (2) ts-order-service shows intermittent socket spikes (5 points) during the window. (3) ts-auth-service displays multi-resource anomalies (cpu, diskio, mem, latency) starting ~15:14–15:22 UTC with sustained increases later in the window. (4) ts-route-service has resource anomalies ~15:14–15:16. (5) ts-travel-service shows error=0 anomalies later (~15:34) for 5 points. Traces aggregate counts indicate heavy interaction between ts-auth-service and ts-order-service.\n\nPer the diagnosis rules, we must (a) confirm faults are consecutive sub-series (not isolated spikes), (b) establish the first occurrence time of each fault, and (c) use traces to pick the downstream-most faulty service in call chains. The metric point lists already show consecutive points for the candidate KPIs, but we still need trace-level evidence of which service is downstream and whether RPC-level error_rate or row_count dropped (which would indicate traffic loss or propagation). Also check service logs for error_count or row_count changes. Thus, the next step is to inspect trace aggregates in the incident window for inter-service calls among the candidate services (auth, order, route, travel, train) to see where error_rate or row_count anomalies appear and their timestamps. This will help decide if a downstream service is faulty or if a lower-level resource (CPU/disk) on an upstream service caused the failure.",
